@flexiarg ukrns/provision-at-network-scale
@title Provision at Network Scale, Selectively
@keywords subsidiarity, scale-choice, capability-trade-off, role-codebook, role-leverage, EV_analyse, asymmetric-trade-off, network-property, selective-provisioning, contextual-fit, comparability
@audience UKRN-S design, UKRN leadership, Research England, participating institutions
@tone analytic-foundational
@style pattern
@references [ukrns/ARGUMENT equity/protected-interaction equity/contribution-pathways equity/visible-impact ukrns/diagnose-before-prescribing]

! conclusion: Each candidate shared capability — evaluation analysis, coordination/liaison, scaffold maintenance — can sit at either the per-institution scale or the network-services scale, and each location gains something while losing something else.  The axis between per-institution contextual fit and network-level scale and comparability recurs for every capability; the service states, for any capability, the composition it is running and the gains and losses at each location.
  + context: The UKRN WP §2 (draft-16-april) analysis of Cycle-0 roles identifies capabilities compressed into single-person, multi-role positions — the signature of absorbed mode at the role level.  A single person informally performs four to six roles that should be distributed; cross-institutional evaluation (EV_analyse) was absent across 4/4 transcripts.  The equity patterns diagnose this at institutional scale (protected-interaction, contribution-pathways, visible-impact).  This design pattern asks, per capability, where the network's provisioning produces the best return — and refuses to treat 'put everything at network scale' as a uniform answer.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: per-institution contextual fit ↔ network-level scale and comparability.
    Real: each capability has a genuine local context to lose (materials fit to local pedagogy, relationships to local leadership, trust of a known actor) and a genuine network scale to gain (value-of-information targeting, cross-institution comparability, lower aggregate maintenance cost, one capacity serving many).  Both endpoints are populated.
    Irreducible: context and comparability are not the same thing.  A network-level evaluation analyst sees across institutions but cannot absorb each institution's lead time and local idiom; a per-institution analyst absorbs context but cannot compare.  No capability can be simultaneously maximally contextual and maximally comparable.
    Active: the location appropriate for a given capability may shift as the network grows and as evidence accrues.  An evaluation analysis function absent at local scale (4/4 transcripts) may become partially locally-viable after Step 2 of the bootstrap; a coordination role viable locally today may become too context-heavy as the network expands.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Capability-by-capability: provision evaluation analysis at network scale (where local provisioning was empirically not happening), keep coordination distributed with a single network-level point of contact, and let scaffold maintenance settle between.  Gives up single-narrative simplicity; demands per-capability argument.
    (2) Everything at network scale: provision all shared capabilities at network scale, accepting the contextual loss and adding a periodic local-review cycle to surface drift.  Gives up local ownership and context-in-the-loop.
    (3) Convening-only: keep everything local and use UKRN-S only as a convening body, accepting that evaluation analysis will remain under-provisioned for the foreseeable future.  Gives up the network-scaling benefit for the capabilities that most need it.
    These compositions are not ranked; each gives up different things, and the right choice for each capability may change over time.
  + BECAUSE:
    Role-leverage (Cycle-0 empirics): Capabilities that benefit all institutions should be provisioned once at the network-services level, not replicated per institution.  The role-codebook's 'single person performing 4-6 roles' is the mirror-image symptom: a structural absence compressed into individual effort.  The structural fact is that some capabilities have positive role leverage (one network instance serves many institutions); others do not.

    Asymmetric trade-off: The trade-off shape differs capability by capability.  For evaluation analysis, local-side loss is empirical (absent 4/4); network-side loss is political-structural (single point of capacity risk, no contextual lead time).  For coordination, both sides are populated: context-aware local relationships vs. network-level view and shared state.  For scaffold maintenance: local pedagogy fit vs. single canonical reference with lower aggregate maintenance cost.  The service articulates each separately — which is why Composition (1) is the analytical default even if it is not the communicative default.

    Subsidiarity (Ostrom-adjacent, evidence-qualified): Provision at the scale where the capability pays off, not at a uniform scale for political tidiness.  The Cycle-0 data provides evidence: for evaluation analysis, the local scale has shown empirical incompetence; for coordination, both scales retain partial competence; the decision has to carry the evidence.

    Equity-pattern answers: This design pattern answers three equity patterns at once.  protected-interaction (breadth overload) is partly answered by network provisioning of coordination support.  contribution-pathways is partly answered by network provisioning of stewarded community infrastructure.  visible-impact is mostly answered by network provisioning of the evaluation chain.  The design pattern's coherence follows from the coherent pattern of institutional failures it responds to.

    Post-dependency lesson: The ORP-era ORCA role was Research-England-funded and did not persist past the programme.  Capabilities designed to sit at network scale must be designed to survive the funding cycle of the coalition that built them; otherwise the 'growth ring' evaporates (linked: ukrns/open-the-triangle).
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: the programme can state, for any capability, the gains and losses at each location on the axis and why it sits where it sits; the scale choice is revisited as the network grows.
    Failing when: capabilities default to one location because the alternative was not considered; a capability's location is never revisited as the network grows; the scale choice is uniform across capabilities despite the asymmetric trade-off shape.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Maintain a capability-by-capability register stating local gain/loss, network gain/loss, and chosen scale with the evidence supporting it
    - For evaluation analysis: provision at network scale with named analyst capacity (resolves equity/visible-impact at scale)
    - For coordination/liaison: support whichever local actor (Institutional Lead, Local Network Lead, self-nominated member) the institution nominates, backed by network-level liaison capacity
    - For scaffold maintenance: single canonical reference with clearly-flagged local-variation channels (resolves equity/shared-maintenance upstreaming)
    - Design every network-scale capability to persist beyond funding cycles of specific posts
    - Use this pattern downstream of ukrns/diagnose-before-prescribing (which profile → which provisioning choice) and upstream of ukrns/measure-where-least-sure (measurement works on whatever scale the capability sits at)
  + INVARIANT-STATEMENT:
    Each shared capability has an explicit, published scale choice supported by the Cycle-0 empirical evidence and the local/network trade-off analysis.  Network-scale capabilities are designed to survive beyond the funding cycle of the coalition that built them.  Scale choices are revisable as new evidence arrives.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Uniform scale-up: 'UKRN-S owns everything' — overshoots on capabilities where local context is load-bearing
    - Uniform default-to-local: 'each institution owns its copy' — recreates the absorbed-mode role compression Cycle 0 documented
    - Asymmetry-blindness: treating evaluation analysis, coordination, and scaffold maintenance as the same trade-off shape
    - Post-dependency: network capability tied to a specific funded role (the ORCA lesson); capability evaporates when the role ends
    - Hidden scale choice: capability is provisioned somewhere but the reasoning is not published; institutions cannot contest
    - Context-blindness: network provisioning without a route for local context to inform the network-level work
    - Frozen location: capability placement never revisited as the network grows
  + ANCESTORS:
    - UKRN WP draft-16-april §2 Pattern (capability trade-off table; role-codebook reanalysis; EV_analyse absence; explicit Tension/Composition/Check)
    - Role codebook: 12 roles, 61 action codes, compression of 4-6 roles into single persons (absorbed-mode signature)
    - ORCA precedent: Research-England-funded posts that do not persist; the negative example for post-dependent design
    - equity/protected-interaction (breadth overload partly answered by network-scale provisioning)
    - equity/contribution-pathways (community infrastructure answered by network-scale stewardship)
    - equity/visible-impact (evaluation chain answered primarily by network-scale provisioning)
    - Ostrom (1990) subsidiarity principle (evidence-qualified form)
  + DERIVATION:
    Derived from UKRN WP draft-16-april §2's capability trade-off analysis, Cycle-0 role-codebook findings, and explicit Tension/Composition/Check structure.
    Answers three equity patterns simultaneously at service scale: protected-interaction, contribution-pathways, visible-impact.
    Mapped to the learning loop at the 'provision' step: after diagnosis names the binding constraint, scale choice places the answering capability where it pays off.
    Deepened via asymmetric trade-off analysis: different capabilities have different trade-off shapes; the service articulates each rather than averaging them.
    Axis framing follows paper-draft-16-april; real / irreducible / active defence and three named compositions are load-bearing.
    Coordination requirement: Medium (service + institution per capability) to Very high (multi-institution provisioning for the evaluation chain).
